\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Due to the inductive characteristic of transcription context, we formulate the question also inductively, as follows:}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \\begin\{mmdef\}[Semantic validity of a transcription]\\label\{def:valid-transcription\}}
\par\pard\plain \tx720\ri-16872\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Assume transcribendum $e_n \\in \\ont\{O\}$, transcriptum $e_n\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92 \\in \\ont\{O\}\u8217\'92$, correspondence $\\mu_n = \\tuple\{ e_n, e_n\u8217\'92, \\theta_n \}$, transcription context $\\ctx_n = \\pair\{r, \\theta_n, r', \\ctx_\{n-1\}\}$ and a semantic valid transcription at one lower level, $\\vldtranscript\{\\theta_\{n-1\}\}$. We denote the transcription result as $t_n\u8217\'92$, and express it inductively as a logical combination of $e_n\u8217\'92$, $e_\{n-1\}\u8217\'92$ and $\\hat\{e\}_\{n-1\}\u8217\'92$. Then, we call the transcription \\emph\{semantically valid\} iff:\\[}
\par\pard\plain \tx720\ri-16872\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \\intn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92(t_n\u8217\'92) \\subseteq \\intn(e_n)}
\par\pard\plain \tx720\ri-16872\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \\]}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \\end\{mmdef\}}
\par\pard\plain \tx720\ri-16872\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \tx720\ri-16872\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 In other words, a transcription is valid if all individuals that potentially belong to the set represented by $e_n$ also belong to the set that can be represented by some logical combination of $e_n\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92$, $e\{n-1\}\u8217\'92$ and $\\hat\{e\}_\{n-1\}\u8217\'92$.}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
